bug.short_desc: Cannot compile project when a java file contains $ in its file name

long_desc.thetext:
A file from soot project has a file ASTNode$State.java. Previous versions of eclipse work well, but juno cannot process it.
-- Configuration Details -- Product: Eclipse 1.5.1.20120828-0743 (org.eclipse.epp.package.java.product) Installed Features: org.eclipse.jdt 3.8.1.v20120814-104540-8-8nFqpFNOfwKDRVz-tXOcL5d_83

Can you tell me what exactly happens? Also let me know if you see any error/exception in the log file.
I am able to open/edit/compile a similarly named file without any problem with the same JDT/Core version.

Created attachment 222760 bug snapshot
You can see that the ASTNode$State cannot be resolved. However, this file is really there in the project file list (left hand side panel). Actually, if I change the file name to be ASTNodeState, all errors are gone.
The project is here (https://github.com/Sable/soot), you can download and try.

After cloning soot from github and also fetching jasminclasses and setting-up projects so that jasmin can be resolved, I can now reproduce the problem.
Here's a workaround for now: Open file ASTNode.java, make a whitespace change and save. After that all errors should be gone.

Created attachment 222830 proposed patch
Simply swapping the order of lookup fixes the immediate issue.
I'm currently running the tests to see what will break by this change ;-P

The history of NameEnvironment tells me that the lookup using the full name has been added only recently, viz for bug 377401. As this changes is comparably young I have hopes that changing statement order in this section does not conflict with other concerns.
Still waiting for test results, looking good so far.

Created attachment 222835 test & fix for master
Status:
- on R3_8_maintenance tests with -Dcompliance=1.7 where green.
- next I created a regression test, which taught me the following dependency: The bug only occurs if ASTNode.java and ASTNode$State.java are both served from NameEnvironment#additionalUnits This means that # units must exceed AbstractImageBuilder.MAX_AT_ONCE, *and* order of units must ensure that the mentioned units are above the threshold, while another unit must exist that refers to ASTNode.java, (below threshold)
- after porting the patch over to master I launched all JDT/Core tests, and so far I'm seeing 10 regressions. I'll investigate this difference when the test run has completed.

I'll investigate this difference when > the test run has completed.
